workflow.name: Transfer workflows with credentials & sub-workflow management between n8n instances
workflow.description:
*This workflow contains community nodes that are only compatible with the self-hosted version of n8n.*

# Export Workflows Between n8n Instances
Copy workflows between n8n instances ‚Äî with optional credential export and automatic sub-workflow adjustments.

## üß† How it Works
This workflow copies a selected workflow from a **SOURCE** n8n server to a **TARGET** server and guides you through safe checks:

- **Name conflict check**: If a workflow with the same name exists on the target the export is stopped.
- **Sub-workflows**: Detects calls to sub-workflows.
  - If all sub-workflows exist on the target (same names), references are auto-updated and the export continues.
  - If any are missing, the form shows what‚Äôs missing and lets you cancel or proceed anyway.
- **Credentials**: Detects nodes using credentials and lets you export those credentials along with the workflow.
  - The workflow can only apply credential corrections for the credentials that you choose to export with it. 
  - At the end, the form lists which credentials were successfully exported.

üí° For in-depth behavior and edge cases, see the Notes inside the workflow (Setup, How It Works, and Credential Issues).

## üöÄ How to Use
1. Run this workflow on your **SOURCE** server.  
2. Follow the step-by-step form: pick the workflow to export, choose whether to include credentials, and review sub-workflow checks. Done.

## ‚öôÔ∏è Setup
- Create an **n8n API key** on both servers (SOURCE and TARGET).
- On the SOURCE server, create **two n8n API credentials** in n8n: one for SOURCE and one for TARGET (using the respective base URL and key).
- Configure the nodes in this workflow with these two credentials.
- Detailed step-by-step instructions are available in the workflow notes.


‚úÖ Once configured, you‚Äôll be ready to migrate workflows between servers in just a few clicks.

# Setup
To set up this workflow, you will need n8n API credentials for both of your systems: **SOURCE** and **TARGET**.  
You can find instructions on how to create credentials [here](https://docs.n8n.io/credentials/).  
Nodes that require configuration are highlighted in red.

### n8n API
- In your n8n settings, open the **n8n API** section from the sidebar.
- Click **Create an API Key**. Give the key a name and save it. The key will only be shown once ‚Äî make sure to copy it for the next steps.
- Repeat these steps for both the SOURCE and TARGET systems. You will now have one API key for each.
- Next, create credentials in the **SOURCE** system only:
  - Add two new **n8n API** credentials using the keys you just created.
  - Configure the server address for each.
  - Create one credential for the SOURCE system and another for the TARGET system, each with its respective key and address.

### System File Paths
- Some nodes access the local file system of the SOURCE system.
- The file paths currently configured are based on a default queue-mode Docker installation.
- Review these paths and update them as needed to match your environment.



‚úÖ **Your workflow is ready!** Run this workflow on your SOURCE system to export workflows to the TARGET system.

# Workflow Exporter

This workflow automates the process of copying workflows and credentials from one n8n server to another. It also checks whether the exported workflow requires adjustments for sub-workflow execution on the target system.

## How It Works
- **Workflow name check**: The system verifies if a workflow with the same name already exists in the target system. If it does, the export is stopped.
- **Sub-workflow check**:  
  - If the exported workflow calls other sub-workflows, the system checks if those sub-workflows already exist in the target system with the same names.  
  - If all sub-workflows are found, the system updates the references so the exported workflow uses the sub-workflows in the target system and continues the export.  
  - If any required sub-workflow is missing, the form will display this and give the user the option to cancel the export so they can fix it first.  
  - If the user decides to continue anyway, the system will update the workflow using only the sub-workflows that exist in the target system (if any).  
- **Credentials check**:  
  - If the exported workflow does not contain nodes with credentials, the export completes normally.  
  - If credentials are configured in the exported workflow, the form will display them and give the user the option to export them along with the workflow or export only the workflow.  
  - Due to n8n and its API limitations, it is not possible to verify whether the credentials already exist in the target system. **See the blue note for details on credential export issues.**  
  - The system can only apply corrections to credentials in the exported workflow if those credentials are exported together with it, since checking credentials already present in the target system is not possible.

## Usage
When you run this workflow, a form will appear.  
- Click **Next** to start the export steps.  
- The next form will display the workflows available in the source system.  
- Select one to export and click **Next**.  
- The form will then guide you through the export process step by step.  



*(See the Setup section for instructions on how to configure this workflow.)*

# Credential Issues and Limitations

As explained in the instructions, the system can only automatically update the exported workflow to use the credentials that are exported along with it.  
Due to limitations in n8n and its API, it is not possible to check whether credentials already exist in the target system. In addition, some special cases may cause credential export to fail due to inconsistencies in the schemas of certain credential types.  

Below are the technical details of these issues:

- The n8n API does not provide the ability to query credentials ‚Äî only to create and delete them.  
- This limitation prevents checking whether credentials already exist in the target system and also complicates copying them.  
- To work around this, the **c8n-cli** utility is used in the source system. Credentials to be exported are first obtained through a local export in file format. This is the only way to retrieve the credential data.  
- However, this method introduces technical inconsistencies with certain credential types.  
- For some credentials, the fields obtained through **c8n-cli** are not consistent with the mandatory fields required by the n8n API when importing them into the target system.  
- As a result, even if the user chooses to export credentials along with the workflow, some credentials may still fail during the process.  
- After the export is complete, the form will list the credentials that were successfully exported.

The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.

data.details: The Code node allows you to execute JavaScript in your workflow.

The Filter node can be used to filter items based on a condition. If the condition is met, the item will be passed on to the next node. If the condition is not met, the item will be omitted. Conditions can be combined together by AND(meet all conditions), or OR(meet at least one condition).
